data.name: Config_Name.ToolTip
data.value: Enter a unique name for each configuration. You can have more than one configuration referencing a single database, or multiple configurations referencing multiple databases. Configurations can be password protected in the ‘Security’ section below, to restrict access to children for example.

data.name: PathStorage.ToolTip
data.value: Enter the full path to the folder/s containing the movie files. You can enter several different paths separated by a semi-colon and you can select the option “search in sub-folders”, if required. You can also use the browse button to locate the correct folder/s.

data.name: AntStorage.ToolTip
data.value:
Select the name of the field in your AMC database that you have used for the movie’s file name / path information.
This field in the AMC database can contain a single filename or multiple file names separated by a semi-colon. If the movie comprises many files, then you could also use a playlist file (.m3u), or an image file (.iso, .bin) or a folder name (containing DVD files or .avi files).
If you have configured a "Path for Movies File Search", the filename is sufficient, otherwise the field requires the fully qualified name including path to the moviefile.

data.name: CatalogType.ToolTip
data.value: Select the type of xml catalog file (AMC, DVDP, MyMovies …..). Types other than AMC will have a temporary file generated each time the original file is modified (based on the ‘date modified’). The generated file is fully compatible with AMC and is stored in the same path as the original file and named “Catalog_File_without_extension”.

data.name: groupBox_SortByItem.ToolTip
data.value: You can define additional sort parameters – for example if you wish to sort by the movie’s length, use the database field ‘Length_num’. In the adjacent field you can include a label for this particular sort item, to be displayed in the sort menu – for example ‘Movie Length’.

data.name: groupBox_AntSelectedEnreg.ToolTip
data.value:
If you wish to filter records to be displayed, or records to be excluded for this particular configuration, select the database field/s, select the appropriate operator/s and enter a value for that field/s.
For example, if you have a configuration of movies for children to watch, and you wish to exclude ‘adult’ movies, then store a specific code (e.g. “XXX’) in an unused field in your ANT database and define that field to be NOT included if the value equals ‘XXX’. Define this configuration by default and a menu of other configurations will not appear, so children will not be aware of any other configurations.
Adult movies can then be included in another configuration that is password protected.

data.name: chkGlobalUnwatchedOnly.ToolTip
data.value:
Unwatched option acts as global overlayfilter for all views and this setting is used for start view. It can be switched on/off from the GUI during runtime. So you should only activate this if you want to filter your views always when entering MyFilms.
You can configure the field and value to identify unwatched films on "update" tab (Watched-Status Handling).

data.name: groupBox_DefaultView.ToolTip
data.value:
Select from the list, the view you want to see when first entering the plugin. Select the option “Display Always that view when using this config”, if you always want to see this view for this configuration. If you do not select the option “Display Always that view when using this config”, the last view used before exiting the plugin will be shown next time.
If a value is entered for the second parameter, only records containing that value will be displayed. For example, you can define a view for children with ‘Category’ – ‘Animation’.

data.name: groupBox_SupplementaryView.ToolTip
data.value: Views by ‘Genre’, by ‘Year’ and by ‘Country’ are already defined by default. In this section you can define additional views; select the database field, enter a label for that field to be displayed in the menu, and then enter a value for the field. If there is no value entered, a menu will be displayed for the range of values available in the database. If a value is entered, a list of the movies with that value will be displayed.

data.name: groupBox_DetailedSupplementaryInformations.ToolTip
data.value: You can enter a unique label and select a database field for any additional information you wish to have displayed for a movie. As this can be skin dependant, some experimentation may be required to see what can be displayed and where it might appear.

data.name: chkWindowsFileDialog.ToolTip
data.value:
If chosen, the option to update the filename / source of the movie will show in the update menu. However, it will be using a standard windows file doalog to browse the filesystem and select the movie file, so it is not recommended to use that option for remote only users.
If using a mouse, this option can be enabled.

data.name: groupBox_AntUpdatingItems.ToolTip
data.value:
Some fields (Rating and Filename) can be updated through the plugin via the Update menu, but you can define two more fields to be updated here. They will show as separate menu entries.
Select the database field to be updated, enter the label associated with that field and enter a pre-defined value to update the field.
A possible use case could be "Checked" "seen" "true" to have a oneclick solution to set a movie watched based on checked DB field.

data.name: groupBox_GrabberOptions.ToolTip
data.value:
If you want to update your movie datas over Internet, valid that option. The grabber will be used for that (grabber.dll file). You have to define the xml parser file to be used with.
With the 'try to find best match automaticly' option validated, the grabber'll try to find best match but can provide errors in some cases. It's better to don't valid it. In taht case, you'll get a menu to choose the right movie.

data.name: Fanart.ToolTip
data.value:
Select the “Use Fanart” option if you have image files to be displayed as background fanart. Enter the full path (or use the browse button) to the root folder containing the fanart image files. There will be one subfolder for each movie, that can contain images with any name. If there are multiple images, they will all be loaded in details view.
Select the option “Use the Default DVD cover for missing Fanart” to have the movie's DVD cover displayed as a background image for movies without a matching fanart file. Be aware, that using that option will often create fanart image of low quality because of low resolution of cover images and you might get a distorted picture as covers and fanarts don't have the same size.

data.name: txtLogosPath.ToolTip
data.value: Enter (or use the browse button) the full path to the folder containing the logo image files. To optimise performance, an image containing all the logos to be displayed for each movie is dynamically created. Those cached images usually are stored in \Thumbs\Myfilms_Logos If you leave the field empty, logos will be searched in <mediaportal program data>\skins\<skin name>\media\logos. Thus the default rules will try to assign logos of the current selected skin, if available. You can use Presets to use default behavior, use B3W logos or use optional logo pack.

data.name: chkLogos.ToolTip
data.value: Select this option if you want the following logos to be displayed for selected items. You can select an existing rule for modification by clicking in the list. Editing is done by changing the settings on the bottom. You have to click "Update Logo Rule" to store changes to the rule.

data.name: SLogo_Type.ToolTip
data.value:
There are two fields referenced in the skin files to display logos - ID2001 and ID2002. You can nominate which logos that you want to see in the first skin field or in the second skin field by referring to these ID numbers.
For example, you can define rules for genre in ID2002 and type of movie (Divx, Xvid, HD...) in ID2001.
If the skin designer has defined two physically distinct fields, you will see two separate logo images. However, if the two fields are defined with the same x and y position values, those two logo files are concatenated and only one image containing both the logos is displayed.
This latter situation is most often the case.

data.name: Config_Dflt.ToolTip
data.value: Check this box for the configuration that you want to be loaded each time the plugin is accessed. If you have more than one configuration, and there are no configurations selected as the default, you will be prompted to select a configuration the first time. Subsequently, the most recent configuration used will be loaded.

data.name: Config_Menu.ToolTip
data.value: If you select this, the Configuration's Menu will be displayed each time you enter in the plugin. You cann't select that option if a Default Configuration is defined If no default config defined and many configs, the configuration to load will be asked the first time After, the plugin load the last configuration used if no default defined

data.name: AntIdentItem.ToolTip
data.value: If the movie file cannot be located, a popup window will advise you that the movie cannot be launched. In the first field you can select the database item that can be used to locate the movie files or the DVD. In the second field you can enter your own text message to provide additional information.

data.name: TitleDelim.ToolTip
data.value:
Character used for hierarchical presentation. This can be used to group more than one movie together, e.g. for collections. This separator can be used in the title fields for "grouping".
Example: Hierachy Separator: "\" movie 1: Moviecollection\movie1 movie 2: Moviecollection\movie2 movie 3: Moviecollection\movie3
Will show "Moviecollection" with 3 items in it.

data.name: groupBox22.ToolTip
data.value:
Select the “Use thumbs for group views" option if you have image files to be displayed as cover image replacement in grouped views. These image files must have the same name as the listitem of the group, e.g. "2010.jpg" or "action.png". Enter the full path (or use the browse button) to your folder containing the view thumb image files.
Select the option 'Use the default movie cover for missing thumbs' if you wish to use a movie cover when no thumb for views is available.
You can also use fanart for those views, to do so, put fanart in the subfolder for year, category, country, e.g. <fanartfolder>\\_group\\year\2010"; The setting for this path is done via the Fanart path setting automatically; See "Resulting path for Group Views fanart"

data.name: PathStorageTrailer.ToolTip
data.value: Enter or select the path for extended search for trailers. MyFilms will try to find matching media files based on the title chosen for trailer search and media files in subdirectories containing the movie name. You can add more than one searchpath by separating them with semicolon, e.g. "path1; path2". If you choose a new path it will be added to your existing path(es).

data.name: SearchFileNameTrailer.ToolTip
data.value: If Trailer file is not found with the 'DB Item for storing Trailer Infos' field, you can search the trailer file with the movie Name. Validate that option for it and give the Title used for the search. Attention: Might degrade performace!

data.name: AntStorageTrailer.ToolTip
data.value: Choose the DB fireld where MyFilms should store the infos about the source path of trailers. "Borrower" is a good recommendation, as it's not commonly used. However make sure, yoiu do not use this field for other purposes (e.g. seen status)

data.name: groupBox24.ToolTip
data.value: The Trailer section allows to use a selectable DB field to store trailer source path infos and thus to integrate trailers into MyFilms. Trailer can be searched within the plugin and "autoregistered". GUI allows to show if a trailer is present (registered) and play it. By default, the search includes mediafiles in the directory of the main movie and it's subdirectories, searching for mediafiles containing "trlr" or "trailer" in the filename. So to enable MyFilms to find and register trailers, you can drop them in the movies directory or a subfolder and make sure they are named accordingly (many downloader utilities do it this way). You can add an additional trailer search path that will search and register for media files containing the movie's title.

data.name: DefaultCover.ToolTip
data.value: Enter the full path and file name of the image file that you wish to use as the default cover image. You can use the browse button to select the file. The default cover image will be displayed when a movie entry does not have an associated cover image and it will be used as a default fanart image if the appropriate Fanart option is selected in the ‘Picture’ section, and a movie entry does not have an associated fanart image.

data.name: DefaultCoverArtist.ToolTip
data.value: Enter the full path and file name of the image file that you wish to use as the default Artist image. You can use the browse button to select the file. The default Artist image will be displayed when an artist does not have an associated photo or image and it will be used as a default artist image.

data.name: MesFilmsImgArtist.ToolTip
data.value: Enter the full path to the folder containing the Artist image files. Matching will be done based on images filename that matches the person's name. You can use the browse button to find the correct path.

data.name: LogoView.ToolTip
data.value: This is the overview of all your defined Logo rules. Each line presents a rule, that is checked for logo display. You can add new rules by setting the rule in the lower part of this screen and press "add" to add it to the ruleset. If you select a rule, you can edit / change it. To make changes stored, you have to click "Update Logo Rule" - otherwise changes are not permanent.

data.name: groupBox_Separators.ToolTip
data.value:
Genre, country and actors are grouped in unique fields in the database and sometimes there are multiple entries in each of these fields which may be separated by commas - for example Genre = 'Comedy, Comedy Romantic, ... ‘ The actual separators used can vary depending on the web-site used to grab the movie information.
When using the ‘Search’ function, the plugin needs to know exactly which separators are used in your movie database. A pre-defined list of separators is already given.
For actors, their names are often followed by a role (Clint Eastwood (Inspector Harry), or Clint Eastwood as Inspector Harry,... ). The plugin needs to know what separator is used to indicate the role text for finding or searching on actors.

data.name: groupBox_SupplementarySearch.ToolTip
data.value:
The following searches are implemented as fixed search options: by films by actors
You can add additional searches by selecting the database field and adding a value to filter that field by, if required. Those searches will be shown as separate entries in the search menu. They obey the filtersettings, so will be based on views you have defined.

data.name: CheckWatched.ToolTip
data.value: Select this option if you want the configured “Watched” field of your database to be updated each time a movie is launched. You will have the option in the GUI to switch to "unwatched movies only" - based on the update of the "Watched" field

data.name: groupBox_TitleOrder.ToolTip
data.value:
title selection: You can set the mapping of the master title, secondary title and sort title to DB-fields to match your catalog.
Grouping: Using a hierarchy separator allows you to do grouping of your films and have a hierarchical presentation. This can be used to group more than one movie together, e.g. for collections.
Example: Hierachy Separator: "\" movie 1: Moviecollection\movie1 movie 2: Moviecollection\movie2 movie 3: Moviecollection\movie3
Will show "Moviecollection" with 3 items in it.

data.name: textBoxGlobalUnwatchedOnlyValue.ToolTip
data.value:
By Default, unwatched items are identified by having either "false" or "" (empty) in the related field. The field used for watched / unwatched status can be configured in the Update Tab.
However, you can define a value other than that, if you require it.

data.name: groupBox2.ToolTip
data.value:
This option allows you updating field info for storing your "watched status".
You can choose field to be used for "watched status" - a good recommendation is "checked".
You can choose to update this field when starting a movie or when playback is finished.
You can update e.g. the "checked" field with a value "true to indicate "watched status".
However be careful not to activate the delete options ("Delete Options", otherwise the physical sourcefiles would get deleted after player finishes!
You will have the option in the GUI to switch to "unwatched movies only" - based on the update of the "checked" field

data.name: groupBoxUpdateByProperties.ToolTip
data.value: In opposite to the "User defined Updating Items", this is used to give you a menu entry to update all fields you define. The difference is, ou can't predefine a value for the update - but will always get a userdialog prefilled with the current value to change the content.

data.name: comboBoxLogoPresets.ToolTip
data.value:
You may choose from several presets to help you getting started. However you can define your logo rules yourself if you want. For selfdefined logorules, the fully qualified path to a logo is stored in the rule, so it might not be fully portable.
"Use skins default logos" is the default and will search for logos in the skindirectory\media\logos and it's subdirectories for logos matching the name in the logo rule. It should work in most situations.

data.name: groupBox1.ToolTip
data.value: Use this area to define a path where cover images are stored. This is mainly required, if you have only image names without full path stored in your DB. You can also define a default cover, that will be used, if there is no cover defined or found for a movie record.

data.name: gpspfield.ToolTip
data.value:
This defines the action taken, when the player finishes. You can update e.g. the "checked" field with a value "true to indicate "watched status". However be careful not to activate the delete options ("Delete Options", otherwise the physical sourcefiles would get deleted after player finishes!
You will have the option in the GUI to switch to "unwatched movies only" - based on the update of the "checked" field

data.name: groupBoxDeletionOptions.ToolTip
data.value:
The Database Deletion Options allow you to update and/or delete records after the corresponding movie is watched.
ATTENTION: Be careful - enabling delete options can delete not only the record in your database, but also the movie linked to it! Update DB = update the record with settings of "Player finished Update Action" Delete DB entry = delete the record from the DB Delete Movie file = PHYSICALLY DELETES your movie from storage medium.
